### 1. Use a single event listener and get the element that triggered the event

You can use the `event.target` property to get the element that triggered the event. This way, you don't need to assign an index to each event listener.

```javascript
stars.forEach((star, index) => {
  star.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(`Star ${star.textContent} was clicked`);
  });
});
```

### 2. Use a data attribute to store the index

You can store the index in a data attribute on the star element and then retrieve it in the event listener.

```javascript
stars.forEach((star, index) => {
  star.dataset.index = index;
  star.addEventListener('click', () => {
    console.log(`Star ${star.textContent} at index ${star.dataset.index} was clicked`);
  });
});
```

### 3. Use a closure to capture the index

You can use a closure to capture the index in the event listener.

